snippet.textDisplay:
Cool cars, they still remain somewhat underrated here in europe. They are going up but nothing close to the prices you're mentioning. 3k would still buy you a decent one here. Only the first model Commodores coupe's (a 6 cil version that optically was close to versions you guys got) are fairly expensive these days. Not to mentioning the original rally versions of other models amongst them the c-kadett coupe, as they are just very hard to find unmolested. My first car was the b1 version of a Opel Manta('78 so the chrome bumper more classic one) a distant cousin to the Torano in that same yellow, as yellow as our Dutch number plates are. Couldn't drive it unnoticed anywhere, like when calling in sick at work and going to your girlfriend instead.. Loved it to bits, a simple rwd chassis you could have a lot of fun with. only a cih 1900 with barely 100bhp but weighing in at no more then a 1000kg on 165 tyres with a low geared 4 speed it was still plenty fun.


The rwd Opel chassis where messed around with a lot when there where still plenty around (80's/90s). Rallied (they still are), bashed or beaten on and/or simply rusted away without the classic car love most other brands got means most have vanished into oblivion. Look into the history of that whole movement on old forums and you'll see a lot interesting options. The CIH were tuneable and the larger 2.2 of 2.4 which swapped right in made them plenty fast on a low budget, 6's found in the bigger sedans(your Commodore) would also fit but made them front heavy. Besides that you guys never got those. Have look at the budget build Holden that hot rod network did. The engine found in that, a C20LET GM product was also a very common swap here. Both NA(a ITB setup sounds glorious) or turbo'd those 16v 4 cil where a reliable source of good power. Sort of a euro SR if you wish, also populair in South America I believe build to very high HP drag specs. It would fit with the car and it combines the continents the chassis was found on. Just a thought.
